## AgentConfig-D3 Architect Soul v2 — Code Verification & Quality Constraints
**Status:** implemented
**Module:** `backend/src/relay/souls/architect.md`
**Tags:** stack:backend
**Depends on:** AgentConfig-D1, AgentConfig-D2, Specs-D8

### Problem

The original Architect soul mandated reading existing specs and writing Architecture/Designs, but it lacked constraints on:
- **Accuracy**: Architects could claim tech stacks or file paths without verification
- **Depth**: Architecture items had structural diagrams but no runtime sequence diagrams
- **Quality**: No self-checklist before handoff, leading to incomplete deliverables

### Solution

Enhance the Architect soul with three new constraint blocks: **Code Verification Mandate**, **Depth Requirements**, and **Quality Checklist**.

#### 1. Code Verification Mandate

Before writing any Architecture or Designs spec that references source code:

| Rule | Enforcement |
|------|-------------|
| Verify tech stack | Dispatch gofer to read `Cargo.toml` and `package.json` before claiming dependencies |
| Verify file existence | Dispatch gofer to confirm file paths and line numbers before citing them |
| Cite code evidence | Every structural conclusion must reference actual code: `backend/src/forge/mod.rs:2024-2076` |

#### 2. Depth Requirements

For every core mechanism described in Architecture:

| Requirement | Format |
|-------------|--------|
| Sequence Diagram | Mermaid `sequenceDiagram` showing runtime behavior |
| Trigger Condition | "When X happens, this mechanism executes" |
| Data Flow | `[input]` → `[processing]` → `[output]` |
| Design Highlight | 1-2 sentences explaining "why this design" |

#### 3. Quality Checklist (self-check before handoff)

```markdown
- [ ] All tech stack claims verified against config files
- [ ] All file paths and line numbers confirmed by gofer
- [ ] Every Architecture item has a Mermaid structural diagram
- [ ] Every core mechanism has a Mermaid sequence diagram
- [ ] Every decision has a Trade-offs table with ≥2 alternatives
- [ ] All class/function/struct names match actual code (not imagined)
- [ ] Every design includes an interface, state machine, and data model
- [ ] No unhandled error cases
- [ ] Explicit data lifecycle definitions
```

### Impact on Profession Configuration

The Architect profession (`backend/src/relay/profession.rs`) already has:
- `owned_sections: [Architecture, Designs]`
- `allowed_tools: [read_specs, write_specs, update_spec, list_specs, read_file, write_file, query_wiki, list_wiki, bring_in, spawn_relay]`

No tool changes are required — the soul constraints are enforced via prompt engineering, not tool gating. The `dispatch` tool (already available via `bring_in` / errand mechanism) is used to spawn gofers for code verification.

### Related Skill Enhancements

The `forge-write-architecture` skill was simultaneously enhanced to require:
- `Sequence Diagram` section in ADR template
- `Code Evidence` section with file path + line range
- `Data Flow` section for runtime behavior
- `Design Highlight` section explaining rationale

### Requirements

- Architect MUST verify tech stack before claiming frameworks
- Architect MUST verify file paths before citing line numbers
- Architect MUST include sequence diagrams for runtime mechanisms
- Architect MUST complete Quality Checklist before handoff
- Quality violations are treated as handoff blockers

